<Layout title="Section 2 – Nursing Process & Clinical Judgment">
  <h1>Section 2: Nursing Process &amp; Clinical Judgment Model</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.2 – Develops a Care Plan</em></p>
  <p>
    Steps of the nursing process (assessment, diagnosis, planning, implementation, evaluation)
    are used to develop a care plan. The clinical judgment measurement model is used to
    determine appropriate person-centered nursing care.
  </p>

  <h2 id="adpie">The Nursing Process (ADPIE)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Assessment</strong> – Collect subjective and objective clinical data.</li>
    <li><strong>Diagnosis</strong> – Identify nursing diagnoses using clinical judgment.</li>
    <li><strong>Planning</strong> – Establish goals and expected outcomes; generate solutions.</li>
    <li><strong>Implementation</strong> – Perform nursing interventions to address patient needs.</li>
    <li><strong>Evaluation</strong> – Determine whether goals were met; revise plan as needed.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="cjmm">Clinical Judgment Measurement Model (CJMM)</h2>
  <p>
    The NCLEX Next Generation uses the CJMM to assess clinical reasoning. The six cognitive
    skills are applied cyclically:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Cognitive Skill</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Recognize Cues</strong></td><td>Identify relevant information from the clinical scenario</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Analyze Cues</strong></td><td>Connect recognized cues to the patient's clinical state</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Prioritize Hypotheses</strong></td><td>Rank hypotheses by urgency and likelihood</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Generate Solutions</strong></td><td>Identify evidence-based interventions for each hypothesis</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Take Action</strong></td><td>Implement the best interventions for the patient</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Evaluate Outcomes</strong></td><td>Assess effectiveness; modify the plan as needed</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="culture-diversity">Culture, Diversity &amp; Health Equity</h2>
  <p>
    Person-centered care requires cultural awareness and humility. Nurses must recognize how
    culture, diversity, and health inequities affect clinical decisions.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Identify the patient's cultural background and how it may affect health beliefs and practices.</li>
    <li>Avoid assumptions; ask open-ended questions to understand the patient's perspective.</li>
    <li>Address language barriers using qualified interpreters (not family members, when possible).</li>
    <li>Recognize that social determinants of health (income, housing, education) impact outcomes.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Cultural Proficiency</strong>
    Cultural competence is a process, not a destination. Striving toward cultural proficiency
    means continuously improving your ability to provide equitable, respectful, individualized care.
  </div>

  <h2 id="plan-of-care">Developing a Plan of Care</h2>
  <p>A nursing care plan includes:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Nursing diagnosis</strong> – Problem, related factor, and evidence (PES format)</li>
    <li><strong>Expected outcomes</strong> – Specific, measurable, achievable, realistic, time-bound (SMART)</li>
    <li><strong>Nursing interventions</strong> – Independent, dependent, and collaborative actions</li>
    <li><strong>Rationale</strong> – Evidence-based justification for each intervention</li>
    <li><strong>Evaluation</strong> – Comparison of actual outcomes to expected outcomes</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Documentation &amp; Reporting</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Use <strong>SBAR</strong> (Situation, Background, Assessment, Recommendation) for structured handoffs.</li>
    <li>Document findings promptly, accurately, and objectively in the EHR.</li>
    <li>Change-of-shift hand-off reports must communicate patient status, pending tasks, and safety concerns.</li>
  </ul>

